Pensacola ([/ˌpɛnsəˈkoʊlə/](/Help:IPA/English) PEN-sə-KOH-lə) is a city nestled in the [Florida panhandle](/Florida_panhandle) of the United States. It holds the distinction of being the [county seat](/County_seat) and the sole [city](/Incorporated_city) within [Escambia County](/Escambia_County,_Florida). As of the [2020 census](/2020_United_States_census), its population stood at 54,312 residents [7]. Pensacola serves as the principal city of the [Pensacola metropolitan area](/Pensacola_metropolitan_area), which, according to the 2020 census, encompassed a population of 509,905.

The history of Pensacola stretches back to its initial settlement by the [Spanish Empire](/Spanish_Empire) in 1559, predating the founding of [St. Augustine](/St._Augustine,_Florida) by a significant six years [9]. However, this early endeavor was tragically cut short by a devastating hurricane, and the area remained unpopulated until its resettlement in 1698 [10]. Pensacola is a vital [seaport](/Port_of_Pensacola) situated on [Pensacola Bay](/Pensacola_Bay). This natural harbor is shielded by the picturesque barrier island of [Santa Rosa](/Santa_Rosa_Island_(Florida)) and provides a crucial connection to the expansive [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico). A cornerstone of the city's identity and economy is the [United States Naval Air Station](/Naval_Air_Station_Pensacola), the very first of its kind established in the United States. This esteemed base is not only home to the world-renowned [Blue Angels](/Blue_Angels) flight-demonstration team but also houses the impressive [National Naval Aviation Museum](/National_Naval_Aviation_Museum). North of the city center lies the [University of West Florida](/University_of_West_Florida), a significant institution of higher learning.

The lands around Pensacola were originally the domain of [Muskogean-speaking](/Muskogean_language) peoples. [Citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) The [Pensacola people](/Pensacola_people), as they were known to Europeans, inhabited the region at the time of first contact. The [Creek people](/Muscogee), also speakers of Muskogean languages, were frequent visitors and traders from the areas now known as southern [Alabama](/Alabama) and [Mississippi](/Mississippi), as well as regions southeast of [Louisiana](/Louisiana). The Spanish explorer [Tristán de Luna](/Trist%C3%A1n_de_Luna) attempted to establish a settlement here in 1559, though it proved to be short-lived. Later, in 1698, the Spanish established a more permanent [presidio](/Presidio), which marked the genesis of the modern city. The strategic importance of Pensacola meant it changed hands numerous times as European powers vied for control in North America. Under [British](/British_West_Florida) rule from 1763 to 1781, the existing Spanish fortifications, though somewhat dilapidated, were repaired and reinforced [12].

The city earned the evocative nickname "the City of Five Flags" due to the succession of five distinct governments that have claimed sovereignty over it throughout its history: Spain ([Castile](/Crown_of_Castile)), [France](/Kingdom_of_France), [Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain), the [United States of America](/United_States)), and the [Confederate States of America](/Confederate_States_of_America). Further adding to its distinctiveness, it is also known as "World's Whitest Beaches" (a tribute to the pristine white sands of the Florida panhandle), "Cradle of Naval Aviation," "Western Gate to the Sunshine State," "America's First Settlement," "[Emerald Coast](/Emerald_Coast)," "[Redneck Riviera](/Redneck_Riviera)," and "P-Cola." Most recently, it has adopted the moniker "The Upside of Florida."

