#### Before European contact

The [Pensacola Bay](/Pensacola_Bay) area was originally inhabited by [Native American](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) peoples. At the time of European arrival, a [Muskogean](/Muskogean)-speaking tribe, known to the Spanish as the [Pensacola](/Pensacola_people), resided in the region. While the name "Pensacola" was not officially recorded until 1677, it is widely believed to be the origin of the names for both the bay and the subsequent city. [13] The [Creek people](/Muscogee), also speakers of Muskogean languages, frequently journeyed from what is now southern Alabama and Mississippi to engage in trade, indicating that the inhabitants were part of a broader network of regional and even continental relations. [14]

The most significant archaeological site associated with the Pensacola culture is the Bottle Creek site, located approximately 59 miles (95 km) west of Pensacola, north of [Mobile, Alabama](/Mobile,_Alabama). This extensive site features at least 18 substantial earthwork mounds, with five arranged around a central plaza. Its primary period of occupation spanned from 1250 to 1550 CE, serving as a crucial ceremonial center and a gateway to the Pensacola society. Access to this site would have been readily available via [dugout canoe](/Dugout_canoe), the primary mode of transportation for the Pensacola people. [15]

#### Spanish

*   Main articles: [Spanish Florida](/Spanish_Florida), [Spanish West Florida](/Spanish_West_Florida), and [Treaty of Paris (1763)](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1763))
*   See also: [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War) and [French and Indian War](/French_and_Indian_War)

The written historical record of the area commences in the 16th century with the accounts of [Spanish explorers](/European_colonization_of_the_Americas), who were the first Europeans to navigate these waters. Expeditions led by [Pánfilo de Narváez](/P%C3%A1nfilo_de_Narv%C3%A1ez) in 1528 and [Hernando de Soto](/Hernando_de_Soto) in 1539 both documented their presence in Pensacola Bay, with de Soto's expedition specifically noting it as the "Bay of Ochuse." [16]

During the [Age of Sail](/Age_of_Sail), Pensacola was renowned as the busiest port along the [Gulf Coast](/Gulf_Coast), boasting the deepest harbor of the region. [17]

The [Spanish Navy](/Spanish_Navy) training ship [Juan Sebastian de Elcano](/Spanish_ship_Juan_Sebasti%C3%A1n_Elcano_(1927)) rendering a [21-gun salute](/21-gun_salute) in honor of Pensacola's 450th anniversary in 2009.

On August 15, 1559, [Tristán de Luna y Arellano](/Trist%C3%A1n_de_Luna_y_Arellano) disembarked with approximately 1,500 individuals from 11 ships originating from [Veracruz](/Veracruz_(city)), Mexico. [18][16][19][20] The expedition's objective was to establish an outpost, which Luna named Santa María de Ochuse, intended to serve as a base for Spanish colonization efforts in [Santa Elena](/Santa_Elena_(Spanish_Florida)) (present-day [Parris Island, South Carolina](/Parris_Island,_South_Carolina)). Tragically, the colony was devastated by a catastrophic [hurricane](/Hurricane) on September 19, 1559, [18][16][20] resulting in the loss of an unknown number of sailors and colonists, the sinking of six ships, the grounding of another, and the ruin of essential supplies.

The surviving colonists faced immense hardship. Many ventured inland towards the region of present-day central Alabama for several months in 1560 before returning to the coast. By 1561, the entire endeavor was abandoned. [18][20] Some survivors eventually made their way to Santa Elena, only to encounter another storm. Those who endured eventually sailed to Cuba and ultimately returned to Pensacola, where the remaining 50 inhabitants were transported back to Veracruz. Consequently, the viceroy's advisors deemed the region too perilous for settlement, and it was largely overlooked for centuries. [18][20]

As the 17th century drew to a close, French explorers began venturing down the [Mississippi River](/Mississippi_River) with aspirations of colonizing the region as part of [New France](/Louisiana_(New_France)). This French activity sparked concern among the Spanish regarding the security of their territories, prompting them to establish a new settlement in western Florida. In 1698, the Spanish founded a fortified town near the location of present-day [Fort Barrancas](/Fort_Barrancas), thereby laying the groundwork for the enduring European-influenced settlement that would evolve into the modern city of Pensacola. [21] The Spanish established three distinct presidios in Pensacola: [22]

*   **Presidio Santa Maria de Galve** (1698–1719): This presidio comprised Fort San Carlos de Austria, situated east of modern [Fort Barrancas](/Fort_Barrancas), and a surrounding village that included a church. [22]
*   **Presidio Isla de Santa Rosa** (1722–1752): The subsequent presidio was located on the western end of [Santa Rosa Island](/Santa_Rosa_Island_(Florida)), near the site of present-day [Fort Pickens](/Fort_Pickens). However, relentless hurricanes battered the island in 1741 and 1752, forcing the garrison to relocate to the mainland. [22]
*   **Presidio San Miguel de Panzacola** (1754–1763): The final presidio was constructed approximately 5 miles (8 km) east of the original presidio. The historic district of downtown Pensacola, which derives its name from "Panzacola," developed around this fort. [22]

During the nascent stages of settlement, a [triracial](/Triracial) [creole](/Creole_peoples) society began to emerge. As a fortified trading post, Pensacola primarily hosted male Spanish soldiers. Some of these men formed relationships or married individuals from the local Pensacola, Creek, or [African](/List_of_ethnic_groups_of_Africa) populations, including both enslaved and free women. Their descendants constituted a mixed-race population, comprising [mestizos](/Mestizo) and [mulattos](/Mulatto). The Spanish actively encouraged [fugitive slaves](/Fugitive_slaves_in_the_United_States) from the [Southern Colonies](/Southern_Colonies) to seek refuge in Florida, offering freedom in exchange for conversion to [Catholicism](/Catholicism). While the majority gravitated towards the area around [St. Augustine](/St._Augustine,_Florida), [23] escaped slaves also found their way to Pensacola.

#### British

*   Main articles: [West Florida](/West_Florida), [British West Florida](/British_West_Florida), [Siege of Pensacola](/Siege_of_Pensacola), [Gulf Coast campaign](/Gulf_Coast_campaign), and [Treaty of Paris (1783)](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1783))
*   See also: [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War) and [Spain and the American Revolutionary War](/Spain_and_the_American_Revolutionary_War)

Following years of Spanish presence, Florida was ceded to the British in 1763 as part of the territorial exchanges that followed Britain's decisive victory over both France and Spain in the [French and Indian War](/French_and_Indian_War) (the North American theater of the [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War)), alongside France's cession of its North American territories. The British designated Pensacola as the capital of their newly established colony of [West Florida](/West_Florida). From 1763 onwards, the British undertook significant efforts to strengthen the defenses around the mainland area of Fort [San Carlos de Barrancas](/San_Carlos_de_Barrancas), constructing the Royal Navy Redoubt. [George Johnstone](/George_Johnstone_(royal_navy)) was appointed as the first British governor, and in 1764, a [colonial assembly](/Colonial_assembly) was instituted. [24][25] The administrative structure of the colony was modeled after that of the existing [British colonies in America](/British_America), diverging from the system employed in [French Canada](/French_Canada). West Florida received an invitation to send delegates to the [First Continental Congress](/First_Continental_Congress), convened to articulate colonial grievances against the British Parliament to [George III](/George_III_of_the_United_Kingdom). However, along with several other colonies, including East Florida, they opted not to attend. Once the [American War of Independence](/American_War_of_Independence) erupted, the colonists in West Florida largely maintained their allegiance to the Crown. In 1778, the [Willing Expedition]((/Willing_Expedition)) embarked on a campaign down the Mississippi River, plundering estates and plantations before ultimately being repelled by a local militia. In the aftermath, the area received a modest contingent of British reinforcements.

The British military resources were notably constrained, and Pensacola ranked relatively low on their list of strategic priorities. Consequently, only a small, symbolic number of British military personnel were ever stationed in Pensacola for its defense. This stands in stark contrast to colonies such as South Carolina, which received substantial British troop deployments. [26] When Spain entered the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution) in 1779, aligning itself with the American rebels, Spanish forces laid siege to Pensacola in 1781, ultimately capturing the city and regaining control of West Florida. [19] Following the conclusion of the war, the British formally ceded both West Florida and [East Florida](/East_Florida) to Spain as stipulated in the postwar [peace settlement](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1783)).

In 1785, a significant influx of Creek people from southern Alabama and [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)) arrived for trade, and Pensacola subsequently flourished as a major commercial hub. It functioned as a garrison town, primarily populated by military personnel and traders. [14] American incursions into the region, coupled with pressure from settlers, propelled the federal government to assert control over this territory.

#### United States

*   Main articles: [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), [Battle of Pensacola (1814)](/Battle_of_Pensacola_(1814)), [Seminole Wars § First Seminole War](/Seminole_Wars), [Adams–Onís Treaty](/Adams%E2%80%93On%C3%ADs_Treaty), [Florida Territory](/Florida_Territory), and [Florida in the American Civil War](/Florida_in_the_American_Civil_War)

During the concluding phases of the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), American troops launched an [offensive against Pensacola](/Battle_of_Pensacola_(1814)), engaging the Spanish and British garrisons defending the city. The conflict concluded with the city's surrender after two days of intense fighting. Pensacola was again occupied by the U.S. in 1818. The pivotal [Adams–Onís Treaty](/Adams%E2%80%93On%C3%ADs_Treaty), negotiated in 1819 between Spain and the United States, formalized American control over Florida in exchange for American recognition of Spanish sovereignty over [Texas](/Texas). [19] A Spanish census conducted in 1820 revealed 181 households within the town, with approximately one-third identified as being of [mixed blood](/Mixed_blood). The population was predominantly composed of French and Spanish Creole individuals. Records, traveler accounts, and paintings from the era, including those by George Washington Sully and [George Catlin](/George_Catlin), document the presence of Indigenous peoples in the area. Creek women were also noted in marriages with Spanish men, appearing in court records and deeds. [14]

With [Andrew Jackson](/Andrew_Jackson) serving as provisional governor, Pensacola officially became part of the United States in 1821. [19] The city was formally incorporated as a municipality in 1822. [2] The Creek people continued to interact with both European Americans and African Americans. However, the dominant White population increasingly enforced rigid binary racial classifications: white and black ("colored," which encompassed [free people of color](/Free_people_of_color), including Indigenous individuals). Nevertheless, American Indians and mestizos were distinctly identified in court and Catholic church records, and in censuses up until 1840, underscoring their recognized presence within the societal structure. Following 1840, the Creek were no longer separately enumerated as Indian, though the people themselves did not vanish. Even after the [removal](/Indian_removal) of many [Seminole](/Seminole) to Indian Territory, individuals of Indigenous descent, often of mixed race but culturally identifying as Muskogean, continued to reside throughout Florida. [14]

A Confederate battery positioned north of Fort McRee in Pensacola, Florida.

Tensions between the White community and Indigenous populations escalated during the era of Indian removal. Furthermore, the growing proportion of Anglo-Americans, who constituted the majority of the White population by 1840, contributed to a hardening of racial discrimination in the region. [14] Social disapproval arose regarding White men cohabiting with women of color, a practice that had previously been more accepted. In 1853, the state legislature enacted a law prohibiting Indigenous people from residing within the state and mandating their capture and removal to Indian Territory. [14]

While this legislation excluded mixed-race Indigenous individuals and those already integrated into White communities, they were compelled to go "underground" to evade persecution. Consequently, no individuals were officially listed as Indian in the late 19th and early 20th-century censuses for Escambia County. People of Indigenous descent were forced to assimilate into either the White or Black communities based on their appearance, effectively "disappearing" from official records. This pattern was replicated in numerous Southern settlements. Children born to White fathers and Indigenous mothers were not designated as Indigenous in the late 19th century, whereas children of Black or Mulatto parentage were classified within the Black community, largely due to the legacy of slavery laws. [14]

Pensacola experienced the upheaval of the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War) when, in 1861, [Confederate](/Confederate_States_of_America) forces suffered a defeat at the nearby [Battle of Santa Rosa Island](/Battle_of_Santa_Rosa_Island). Federal forces of the United States subsequently failed to achieve victory in the [Battle of Pensacola](/Battle_of_Pensacola_(1861)). Following the fall of [New Orleans](/New_Orleans) in 1862, the Confederacy relinquished control of Pensacola, and the city came under Union occupation. [28] In June 1861, the Pensacola Guards were formally mustered into service as a company within the [1st Florida Infantry Regiment](/1st_Florida_Infantry_Regiment). [29]

A North Hill line streetcar proceeds south along Palafox Street, passing militia encampments.

A citywide streetcar strike occurred in Pensacola in 1908, culminating in the deployment of state militia to the city and the declaration of martial law. [30][31]

In 1907–1908, a group of 116 [Creeks](/Muscogee) in Pensacola sought enrollment in the [Eastern Cherokee](/Eastern_Cherokee) registry, mistakenly believing all Indigenous individuals were eligible. Examination of Alabama census records revealed that most of these individuals were, in fact, descendants of Creeks who had relocated to the Pensacola area from southern Alabama following the Indian removal policies of the 1830s. [14]

## Geography

Pensacola is situated on the northern shores of [Pensacola Bay](/Pensacola_Bay). It lies 59 miles (95 km) east of [Mobile, Alabama](/Mobile,_Alabama), and 205 miles (330 km) west of [Tallahassee](/Tallahassee,_Florida), the state capital. While the incorporated city limits of Pensacola are relatively modest in size, a considerable number of [census-designated places](/Census-designated_place) (CDPs) are located immediately adjacent to the incorporated area. These communities are widely considered to be part of the greater Pensacola region. Residents of these CDPs, despite having Pensacola mailing addresses and often lacking independent government services beyond those provided by the City of Pensacola and Escambia County, have previously rejected incorporation into the City of Pensacola through referendums. Nonetheless, they largely identify themselves as Pensacolians. Prominent examples of these CDPs include [Goulding](/Goulding,_Florida), [Ferry Pass](/Ferry_Pass,_Florida), [Ensley](/Ensley,_Florida), [Bellview](/Bellview,_Florida), [Myrtle Grove](/Myrtle_Grove,_Florida), [Warrington](/Warrington,_Florida), [Brent](/Brent,_Florida), and [West Pensacola](/West_Pensacola,_Florida).

Pensacola is located at 30°25′17″N 87°13′2″W&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;30.42139°N 87.21722°W&#xfeff; / 30.42139; -87.21722 (30.4213090, -87.2169149). [6]

According to data from the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), the city encompasses a total area of 41.127 square miles (106.52 km 2 ). Of this, 22.773 square miles (58.98 km 2 ) constitute landmass, while 18.354 square miles (47.54 km 2 ), representing 44.62%, is covered by water. [4]

The topography of the land gently slopes northward from Pensacola Bay. The majority of the city is situated at an elevation sufficiently high to mitigate the impact of potential hurricane storm surges. [32]

### Climate

Weather statistics, meticulously recorded since the late 20th century, are primarily gathered at the local airport. Pensacola has experienced temperatures dipping below single digits Fahrenheit (below 10 °F; −12 °C) on three documented occasions: 5 °F (−15 °C) on [January 21, 1985](/1985_North_American_cold_wave); 7 °F (−14 °C) on [February 13, 1899](/Great_Blizzard_of_1899); and 8 °F (−13 °C) on January 11, 1982. [33] Adhering to the [Köppen climate classification](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification) system, Pensacola is characterized by a [humid subtropical climate](/Humid_subtropical_climate) [34] (Köppen: Cfa). This classification signifies short, mild winters and notably hot, humid summers. Typical summer conditions involve daytime highs in the lower 90s °F (32–34 °C) and nighttime lows in the mid-70s °F (23–24 °C). [35] The prevalence of afternoon or evening thunderstorms is a common feature during the summer months. Owing in part to its coastal positioning, temperatures exceeding 100 °F (38 °C) are relatively infrequent; the last recorded instance occurred in June 2011, when two of the first four days of the month saw highs reach the century mark. [36]

The highest temperature ever officially recorded in the city was 106 °F (41 °C) on July 14, 1980. [35]

Based on the 1991–2020 climate normals, the average daily temperature in January is 53.2 °F (11.8 °C). Freezing temperatures occur, on average, 11 days per winter. The typical first freeze date falls around December 12, and the last freeze around February 14, affording Pensacola an average growing season of 301 days. However, the winter season of 2018-19 notably did not register a freeze. The median dates for the first and last freezes are generally earlier and later, respectively, than the average December 12 and February 14 dates. The median number of freezes per season is typically 11 or fewer. [37]

The mean coldest temperature experienced in a typical winter season hovers around 24 °F (−4.4 °C). The median, however, is slightly higher, rarely dropping below 25 °F (−3.9 °C) in most years, placing Pensacola within USDA zone 9b. Temperatures below 20 °F (−6.7 °C) are exceptionally rare; the last occurrence was on January 8, 2015, [38] when a low of 19 °F (−7.2 °C) was recorded. [39] The absolute lowest temperature ever documented in Pensacola was 5 °F (−15 °C) on [January 21, 1985](/January_1985_Arctic_outbreak). [35]

[Snow](/Snow) is an uncommon occurrence in Pensacola, though it does fall occasionally. The most recent significant snowfall event took place on [January 21, 2025](/January_20%E2%80%9322,_2025_Gulf_Coast_blizzard), resulting in record-breaking accumulations of up to 9.4 inches (24 cm) within the city limits and generating near-blizzard conditions. [40][41] The snowfall event preceding this occurred on [December 9, 2017](/December_2017_North_American_winter_storm). [42] The city receives an average of 68.31 inches (1,740 mm) of precipitation annually, with a slightly more pronounced rainy season during the summer months. July typically records the highest rainfall, averaging 7.89 inches (200 mm), while May is generally the driest month, with approximately 3.90 inches (99 mm). [35] In June 2012, Pensacola and its surrounding areas experienced over a foot (300 mm) of rainfall, leading to widespread flooding. [43] On [April 29, 2014](/Tornado_outbreak_of_April_27%E2%80%9330,_2014), Pensacola was inundated by at least 20 inches of rain within a 24-hour period, triggering the most severe flooding event in three decades. [44]

The city sustained significant damage on February 23, 2016, when a powerful [EF3 wedge tornado](/2016_Pensacola_Tornado) struck the northwestern sector of Pensacola, causing extensive destruction and several injuries. [45]

