### Hurricanes

Damage from [Hurricane Ivan](/Hurricane_Ivan) at a bayou near Naval Air Station, 2004.

Pensacola's geographical position on the [Florida Panhandle](/Florida_Panhandle) renders it particularly susceptible to the impact of hurricanes. Notable hurricanes that have made landfall at or near Pensacola since the late 20th century include [Eloise](/Hurricane_Eloise) (1975), [Frederic](/Hurricane_Frederic) (1979), [Juan](/Hurricane_Juan_(1985)) (1985), [Erin](/Hurricane_Erin_(1995)) (1995), [Opal](/Hurricane_Opal) (1995), [Georges](/Hurricane_Georges) (1998), [Ivan](/Hurricane_Ivan) (2004), [Dennis](/Hurricane_Dennis) (2005), and [Sally](/Hurricane_Sally) (2020). In July 2005, Hurricane Dennis made landfall just east of the city, sparing Pensacola the catastrophic damage it endured from Ivan the previous year. Nevertheless, hurricane-force winds, or near-hurricane-force conditions, were recorded in downtown, leading to moderate damage.

In 2005, Pensacola experienced a glancing blow from [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina), resulting in damage categorized as light to moderate within the affected area. The aftermath of Hurricane Katrina's extensive devastation in neighboring regions led to a significant decline in tourism from [Louisiana](/Louisiana), [Mississippi](/Mississippi), and [Alabama](/Alabama).

#### Hurricane Ivan

*   Main article: [Hurricane Ivan](/Hurricane_Ivan)

On September 16, 2004, [47] Pensacola and its surrounding vicinities were left in ruins by the passage of Hurricane Ivan. Pensacola found itself situated on the eastern periphery of the [eyewall](/Eye_(cyclone)), unleashing a colossal [storm surge](/Storm_surge) into [Escambia Bay](/Escambia_Bay). This surge proved catastrophic for the I-10 [Escambia Bay Bridge](/Escambia_Bay_Bridge), destroying a substantial portion of it. The storm dislodged 58 spans from both the eastbound and westbound sections of the bridge and misaligned an additional 66 spans, rendering the bridge impassable in both directions. [48] The surge also obliterated the fishing bridge that spanned Pensacola Bay, running parallel to the Phillip Beale Memorial Bridge, locally known as the Three Mile Bridge. [49]

The cumulative damage in the metropolitan area exceeded $6 billion, with over 10,000 homes completely destroyed and another 27,000 suffering severe damage. Approximately 105,000 households in [Northwest Florida](/Florida_Panhandle) were impacted in some capacity by the storm, and a staggering 4,300 businesses in the region were forced to close permanently in the wake of Hurricane Ivan. [50] [NASA](/NASA) even generated a comparative image to visually represent the immense scale of the destruction. This widespread property devastation resulted in a severe shortage of affordable housing within the Pensacola real estate market. Furthermore, the subsequent impacts of [Hurricane Dennis](/Hurricane_Dennis) and [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina) exacerbated the existing scarcity of construction labor and essential resources along the [Gulf Coast](/Gulf_Coast_of_the_United_States). [50]

#### Hurricane Sally

*   Main article: [Hurricane Sally](/Hurricane_Sally)

In September 2020, Pensacola endured significant damage from [Hurricane Sally](/Hurricane_Sally). The estimated damages in Escambia County, as reported by local officials, amounted to $29 million. Downtown Pensacola experienced extensive flooding. [51]

