## Economy

The [Blue Angels](/Blue_Angels) performing their aerial maneuvers over [Naval Air Station Pensacola](/Naval_Air_Station_Pensacola).

### Military

The city has earned the moniker "the Cradle of Naval Aviation." [61] [Naval Air Station Pensacola](/Naval_Air_Station_Pensacola) (NASP), commissioned in 1914, holds the distinction of being the first naval air station established by the U.S. Navy. It has been the training ground for tens of thousands of naval aviators, including notable figures such as [John H. Glenn](/John_H._Glenn), USMC, who achieved the historic feat of becoming the first American to orbit the Earth in 1962, and [Neil Armstrong](/Neil_Armstrong), the first human to walk on the Moon in 1969. [62] NASP is also the home base for the Navy's elite Flight Demonstration Squadron, the [Blue Angels](/Blue_Angels).

The [National Museum of Naval Aviation](/National_Museum_of_Naval_Aviation), located on NASP, offers free admission to the public. This museum meticulously curates and displays hundreds of vintage naval aviation aircraft, preserving the rich history of naval aviation through its extensive exhibits, symposiums, captivating IMAX films, and guided tours.

[Information Warfare Training Command Corry Station](/Corry_Station_Naval_Technical_Training_Center) functions as an annex to the main base and serves as the operational hub for the [Center for Information Warfare Training Command](/Information_Dominance_Corps). The CWO3 Gary R. Schuetz Memorial Health Clinic is situated at Corry Station, within Naval Hospital Pensacola, which also houses the primary Navy Exchange and a [Defense Commissary Agency](/Defense_Commissary_Agency) commissary complex serving both Corry Station and NAS Pensacola. Additionally, the Army National Guard's B Troop 1-153 Cavalry and Bravo Company of the 146th Expeditionary Signal Battalion are stationed in Pensacola.

NASP recently hosted the commissioning ceremony for the United States Navy's newest [amphibious transport dock](/Amphibious_transport_dock), the USS Richard M. McCool Jr. (LPD 29), on September 7, 2024. The ceremony was graced by the presence of Shana McCool, the granddaughter of [Richard M. McCool Jr.](/Richard_Miles_McCool), who served as the ship's sponsor. Esteemed attendees included the [secretary of the Navy](/United_States_Secretary_of_the_Navy) and the [chief of naval operations](/Chief_of_Naval_Operations). The USS Richard M. McCool Jr. is the 13th vessel of the San Antonio-class to be commissioned into the United States Navy and is the first ship to bear the name of Richard M. McCool Jr. [63][64]

### Tourism

Pensacola is a vibrant hub for a variety of annual [festivals](/Festival), events, historical tours, and landmarks. The Pensacola Seafood Festival and the Pensacola Crawfish Festival have been cherished traditions in the city's historic downtown for nearly three decades. The [Great Gulfcoast Arts Festival](/Great_Gulfcoast_Arts_Festival), held annually in November at Seville Square, consistently attracts over 200 artists from both regional and international backgrounds. The Children's Art Festival, also hosted in Seville Square, provides a platform for showcasing the artistic talents of local schoolchildren. [Pensacon], a popular comic convention, takes place each February and draws nearly 25,000 attendees from across the globe. The Pensacola Interstate Fair is a highly anticipated annual event held each fall. [65]

[Scuba diving](/Scuba_diving) and [deep-sea fishing](/Deep-sea_fishing) are integral components of Pensacola's thriving tourism industry. In 2004, the USS Oriskany was deliberately sunk off the coast of Pensacola to create a significant artificial reef. [66]

Numerous walking tours are available in Pensacola, offering visitors an intimate exploration of its meticulously restored 18th-century neighborhoods.

Pensacola is also home to the [Vietnam Veterans' Wall South](/Vietnam_Veterans_Memorial). The city boasts a number of historically significant military installations dating back to the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War), including [Fort Barrancas](/Fort_Barrancas). [Fort Pickens](/Fort_Pickens) notably served as a temporary place of confinement for the legendary Apache leader [Geronimo](/Geronimo). Additional military landmarks of interest include the [National Naval Aviation Museum](/National_Naval_Aviation_Museum) and the iconic [Pensacola Lighthouse](/Pensacola_Lighthouse) located at NASP.

The city's convention and visitors bureau, Visit Pensacola, [67] operates under the auspices of the Greater Pensacola Chamber. [68]

