## Arts and culture

### The arts and theatre

The Saenger Theatre in Downtown Pensacola.

Pensacola offers a diverse array of performance venues. The [Pensacola Bay Center](/Pensacola_Bay_Center) (formerly the Pensacola Civic Center) [70] frequently hosts major events, while the historic [Saenger Theatre](/Saenger_Theatre_(Pensacola,_Florida)) is utilized for a range of performances, including mid-level productions. Other notable venues for live performances, theatrical plays, and musicals include the Pensacola Little Theatre, Pensacola State College, the University of West Florida, Vinyl Music Hall, and Loblolly Theatre. Pensacola is also the proud home of the [Pensacola Opera](/Pensacola_Opera), the Pensacola Children's Chorus, the Pensacola Symphony Orchestra, the Pensacola Civic Band, the Pensacola Bay Concert Band, and the Choral Society of Pensacola. The city also boasts Ballet Pensacola and the vibrant [Palafox Place](/Palafox_Place) entertainment district.

### Architecture

[Seville Tower](/American_National_Bank_Building_(Pensacola,_Florida)) in Pensacola.

While Pensacola does not possess a towering skyline, it features several notable low-rise structures. The tallest among them is the Crowne Plaza Grand Hotel, standing at 15 floors and reaching a height of 146 feet (45 m). Other significant tall buildings include the Scenic Apartments (98 feet; 30 m), SunTrust Tower (96 feet; 29 m), [Seville Tower](/American_National_Bank_Building_(Pensacola,_Florida)) (88 feet; 27 m), and the AT&T Building (76 feet; 23 m).

Among the city's architecturally significant historic buildings is the [First National Bank Building](/First_National_Bank_Building_(Pensacola,_Florida)).

