### Pelican Drop

The Pelican Drop was a prominent [New Year's Eve](/New_Year%27s_Eve) celebration held annually in downtown Pensacola. During this event, an aluminum effigy of a [pelican](/Pelican), the city's symbolic mascot, was lowered in a manner analogous to the traditional New Year's ball drop. The festivities typically included live musical performances and a spectacular fireworks display. From 2008 to 2018, The Pelican Drop served as a major attraction, drawing crowds of up to 50,000 locals and visitors, solidifying its status as one of the most significant New Year's Eve events in the [Central Time Zone](/Central_Time_Zone_(North_America)). In 2014, the event garnered recognition as one of the top 20 events in the Southeastern United States by the Southeast Tourism Society. [71]

#### History

The inaugural Pelican Drop New Year's Celebration occurred in 2008. The [Pensacola News Journal](/Pensacola_News_Journal) published an article detailing the Pensacola Community Redevelopment Agency's plans for a novel New Year's Eve celebration at [Plaza Ferdinand VII](/Plaza_Ferdinand_VII), which was broadcast live on [WEAR-TV](/WEAR-TV). Beginning with the 2017 celebration, the event's broadcast was extended to WEAR's website via simulcast. The event attracted nearly 45,000 attendees, including residents from Mobile, Alabama (which hosts its own competing drop event featuring a [Moon Pie](/Moon_Pie)), as well as individuals from [Milton, Florida](/Milton,_Florida), [Navarre, Florida](/Navarre,_Florida), and [Destin, Florida](/Destin,_Florida). [72]

In December 2019, organizers announced the cancellation of The Pelican Drop due to financial constraints and the considerable burden the event placed on local law enforcement and public services. A scaled-down fireworks display, requiring less extensive traffic disruption, was planned as an alternative. [73]

The pelican itself was designed and constructed by Emmett Andrews LLC. [74] Crafted from polished aluminum and adorned with over 2,000 lights, the avian sculpture possessed a wingspan of 17 feet (5.2 m) and stood 12 feet (3.7 m) tall. [71]

