The city of Pensacola operates under a strong [mayor-council](/Mayor-council) form of government, a system adopted in 2011 following a voter-approved new city charter in 2009. The elected mayor serves as the chief executive officer of the city administration, while a seven-member city council functions as the primary governing body. The council elects a president and a vice president from among its members.

On June 11, 2013, city voters approved a charter amendment that eliminated the two at-large seats from the then-nine-member council. One seat was phased out in November 2014, and the other concluded its term in November 2016. Further charter amendments, approved on November 4, 2014, introduced the possibility of mayoral recall and granted the city council the authority to appoint staff. The current [city hall](/Pensacola_City_Hall) was inaugurated in 1986.

### Politics

Following the [Civil War](/U._S._Civil_War), Pensacola, much like the rest of the [South](/Southern_United_States), was under [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) control during the [Reconstruction era](/Reconstruction_era_of_the_United_States) (1865–1877). This period saw a significant presence of African American politicians in various capacities, including county commissioners, city aldermen, constables, state representatives, and even one African American mayor, Salvador Pons. However, the election of Edward Perry, a native Pensacolian and former Confederate general, in 1884 marked a substantial political shift. Perry, a [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) who had actually lost the Escambia County vote in the statewide election, proceeded to dissolve the existing Republican city government of Pensacola. In 1885, he replaced it with hand-picked appointees, including the influential railroad magnate William D. Chipley. The sole African American retained in city government was George Washington Witherspoon, an [African Methodist Episcopal Church](/African_Methodist_Episcopal_Church) pastor who, having previously been a Republican, switched his party affiliation to Democratic. Following Governor Perry's dissolution of the Republican administration, the city remained under Democratic leadership for over a century after the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War), with no African Americans holding elected office for nearly a hundred years.

