This political landscape began to change in 1994 when Republican attorney [Joe Scarborough](/Joe_Scarborough) decisively defeated Vince Whibbs Jr., the son of the popular former Democratic mayor [Vince Whibbs](/Vince_Whibbs), to represent [Florida's 1st congressional district](/Florida%27s_1st_congressional_district), which is centered in Pensacola. Republicans also secured all of the area's state legislative seats, a majority of which had previously been held by Democrats. Since that time, Republicans have maintained dominance across all levels of government, notwithstanding the officially nonpartisan nature of municipal elections.

Pensacola is represented in the [United States House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives) by [Jimmy Patronis](/Jimmy_Patronis) ([R](/Republican_Party_(United_States))), who secured the seat in a [special election](/2025_Florida%27s_1st_congressional_district_special_election) following the resignation of [Matt Gaetz](/Matt_Gaetz) ([R](/Republican_Party_(United_States))) in November 2024. In the state senate, the district is represented by [Doug Broxson](/Doug_Broxson) (R), [82] and in the state house, District 2 is represented by [Alex Andrade](/Alex_Andrade_(politician)) (R). [83]

## Education

The primary campus of [Pensacola State College](/Pensacola_State_College) is located within the City of Pensacola. The [University of West Florida](/University_of_West_Florida) (UWF) operates a campus in downtown Pensacola, while its main campus, situated north of the city, houses the [John C. Pace Library](/John_C._Pace_Library), the largest library in the region. UWF stands as the preeminent post-secondary institution in the area.

Public [primary](/Primary_education) and [secondary](/Secondary_education) schools serving Pensacola are administered by the [Escambia County School District](/Escambia_County_School_District). Within the City of Pensacola, the district operates two high schools: [Booker T. Washington](/Booker_T._Washington_High_School_(Pensacola,_Florida)) and [Pensacola](/Pensacola_High_School). Nearby district-run high schools include [Escambia](/Escambia_High_School), [J. M. Tate](/J._M._Tate_High_School), and [Pine Forest](/Pine_Forest_High_School). Other public schools within the city limits are A.K. Suter Elementary, Cordova Park Elementary, J.H. Workman Middle, N.B. Cook Elementary, O.J. Semmes Elementary, and Scenic Heights Elementary. The district also manages one magnet high school, [West Florida High School of Advanced Technology](/West_Florida_High_School_of_Advanced_Technology), located near the city.

Several private educational institutions operate within or in close proximity to Pensacola, including East Hill Academy, East Hill Christian School, Episcopal Day School of Christ Church, [Pensacola Catholic High School](/Pensacola_Catholic_High_School), [Pensacola Christian Academy](/Pensacola_Christian_Academy), Sacred Heart Cathedral School, Saint John the Evangelist Catholic School, Saint Paul Catholic School, Little Flower Catholic School, and Seville Bayside Montessori. The campus of [Pensacola Christian College](/Pensacola_Christian_College) is situated near the city.

## Media

*   Main article: [Escambia County, Florida media](/Escambia_County,_Florida_media)

The primary daily newspaper serving the Pensacola area is the [Pensacola News Journal](/Pensacola_News_Journal), with its editorial offices located on Romana Street in the city's downtown. The News Journal is owned by the [Gannett Company](/Gannett_Company). An alternative weekly publication, *Inweekly*, also serves the community.

Pensacola is home to [WEAR-TV](/WEAR-TV), a dual-affiliated station carrying programming from both [ABC](/American_Broadcasting_Company) and [NBC](/NBC) for the Pensacola, [Navarre, Florida](/Navarre,_Florida), [Fort Walton Beach, Florida](/Fort_Walton_Beach,_Florida), and [Mobile, Alabama](/Mobile,_Alabama) markets. [WSRE-TV], the local [PBS](/Public_Broadcasting_Service) member station, is operated by [Pensacola State College](/Pensacola_State_College). Other television stations broadcasting within the market, all based in Mobile, include [WALA-TV], the Fox affiliate; [WKRG], the [CBS](/CBS) affiliate; and [WPMI], a de facto [owned-and-operated station](/Owned-and-operated_station) of the [Roar](/Roar_(TV_network)) network. Cable television services in Pensacola are provided by [Cox Communications](/Cox_Communications) and [AT&T U-Verse](/AT%26T_U-Verse). [WUWF], the region's [NPR](/NPR) member station, is based at the [University of West Florida](/University_of_West_Florida). [WPCS (FM)], broadcasting from the [Pensacola Christian College](/Pensacola_Christian_College) campus, serves as the studio location for the nationwide Rejoice Radio Network. [84]

Local publications include *Pensacola Magazine*, a monthly glossy magazine, and *Northwest Florida's Business Climate*, the sole business publication dedicated to the region. The *News Journal* also publishes *Home & Garden Weekly* magazine and *Bella*, a monthly publication focused on women's interests.

## Infrastructure

### Transportation

An ECAT bus in June 2006.

#### Aviation

Major air traffic for the Pensacola region and the broader northwest Florida area is managed by [Pensacola International Airport](/Pensacola_International_Airport). By passenger volume, Pensacola International ranks as the largest airport in Northwest Florida and the second busiest in all of [North Florida](/North_Florida), trailing only [Jacksonville](/Jacksonville_International_Airport). [Citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) As of August 2023 [update], the airlines serving Pensacola International Airport include [American Airlines](/American_Airlines), [Delta Air Lines](/Delta_Air_Lines), [Frontier Airlines](/Frontier_Airlines), [Silver Airways](/Silver_Airways), [Southwest Airlines](/Southwest_Airlines), [Spirit Airlines](/Spirit_Airlines), and [United Airlines](/United_Airlines). [85]

#### Railroads

Pensacola's rail connection began with the [Alabama and Florida Railroad](/Alabama_and_Florida_Railroad_(1853%E2%80%931869)), completed in 1861, linking the city to [Montgomery, Alabama](/Montgomery,_Alabama), just prior to the outbreak of the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War). During the war, a significant portion of the rails between Pensacola and the Alabama state line were dismantled to support the construction of other railroad lines deemed more critical elsewhere in the [Confederacy](/Confederate_States_of_America). The Pensacola line was not reconstructed until 1868 and was subsequently acquired by the [Louisville and Nashville Railroad](/Louisville_and_Nashville_Railroad) in 1880. In 1882, the [Pensacola and Atlantic Railroad](/Pensacola_and_Atlantic_Railroad) was completed, extending from Pensacola to [Chattahoochee, Florida](/Chattahoochee,_Florida), thereby connecting Pensacola to the rest of the state. This line also came under the ownership of the L&N.

By 1928, several short lines that had been built northward from Pensacola to [Kimbrough, Alabama](/Kimbrough,_Alabama) were acquired by the [Frisco Railroad](/Frisco_Railroad), granting it access to the port of Pensacola. [86][87] Approximately three decades later, a retired Frisco steam engine, No. 1355, was donated to the city and now stands in the median of Garden Street, near the former site of the demolished Frisco passenger station. [88]

Frisco passenger service to Pensacola concluded in 1955. L&N passenger service, including the streamlined [Gulf Wind](/Gulf_Wind), ceased in 1971 with the introduction of [Amtrak](/Amtrak). However, from early 1993 until August 2005, Pensacola was served by the tri-weekly [Amtrak](/Amtrak) [Sunset Limited](/Sunset_Limited). Service east of [New Orleans](/New_Orleans) to [Jacksonville](/Jacksonville, Florida) and [Orlando](/Orlando, Florida) was suspended due to damage sustained by the [CSX](/CSX) rail line during [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina) in 2005. [89]

In the 21st century, freight service to and from Pensacola is provided by CSX, the successor to L&N, as well as the Alabama and Gulf Coast Railway, the successor to Frisco and a [short line](/Shortline_railroad). On June 1, 2019, the newly established Florida Gulf & Atlantic Railroad, a [Class III railroad](/Class_III_railroad) headquartered in [Tallahassee](/Tallahassee), acquired the CSX main line stretching from Pensacola to [Baldwin, Florida](/Baldwin,_Florida), near [Jacksonville](/Jacksonville), positioning itself as the [Panhandle](/Florida_Panhandle)'s sole east-west freight carrier. A mid-2019 news report concerning the new railroad indicated that Amtrak had assessed the likelihood of passenger service restoration in the Panhandle as "near-zero." [90] Pensacola and Tallahassee remain the two largest metropolitan areas in Florida without any form of passenger rail service.

